**Thoughts**
Adding up by digits.
In the array, we start from the last element.
For the integer k, each time we use the last digit (k % 10),
if the sum is bigger than 9, add 1 to k(so we don't need another var to record it).
After the loop, deal with the case k > 0 (maybe k is too big or we have addup).

**Code**
```java
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> addToArrayForm(int[] num, int k) {
        List<Integer> res = new ArrayList<>();
        int n = num.length;
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            int sum = num[i] + k % 10;
            k /= 10;
            if (sum > 9) {
               k += 1;
               sum -= 10;
            }
            res.add(sum);
        }
        for (; k > 0; k /= 10) {
            res.add(k % 10);
        }
        Collections.reverse(res);
        return res;
    }
}
```

**Time Complexity**
Time: O(N), one for loop
Space: O(1), use one arraylist as result

**Thoughts**
1. Get all indices of c, go through s to compare i with indices of c
2. Traverse s from left side and right side, record the last index of c , so `i - prev` and `prev - i` is the distance for each traverse, at last compare and select the smaller one

**Code**
