```
**Time Complexity**
* Time: O(n)
* Space: O(n)

**Thoughts**

Use an array to simulate the stack, top var to record the index of the top value
Also, use another array to record the value needed to be added. Addition only happens with Popping, if PoP() is called, we start from the top value, add stack\[top] with add\[top], then we add the val in add\[top] to the previous one add\[top - 1], make sure the index in two array are  consistent

**Code**
```java
class CustomStack {
    int[] stack;
    int[] add;
    int top;
    public CustomStack(int maxSize) {
        stack = new int[maxSize];
        add = new int[maxSize];
        top = -1;
    }

    public void push(int x) {
        if (top != stack.length - 1) {
            top++;
            stack[top] = x;
        }
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (top == -1) {
            return -1;
        }
        int ret = stack[top] + add[top];
        if (top != 0) {
            add[top - 1] += add[top];
        }
        add[top] = 0; 
        top--;
        return ret;
    }

    public void increment(int k, int val) {
        int limit = Math.min(k - 1, top);
        if (limit >= 0) {
            add[limit] += val;
        }
    }
}

/**
 * Your CustomStack object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * CustomStack obj = new CustomStack(maxSize);
 * obj.push(x);
 * int param_2 = obj.pop();
 * obj.increment(k,val);
 */
```

**Complexity**
Time: O(1) for all operations
Space: O(n)

**Thoughts**
1. Using two stacks to record the number and characters
2. Traversing s, when it's number(digit), push(c);
			when it's `[`, save current sb to stack;
			when it's `]`, do the multiplication;
			when it's char, append to sb

**Code**
```java
    public String decodeString(String s) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        int multi = 0;
        Deque<Integer> stack = new LinkedList<>();
        Deque<StringBuilder> sbStack = new LinkedList<>();
        for (Character c: s.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isDigit(c)) {
                multi = multi * 10 + c - '0';
            } else if (c == '[') {
                stack.push(multi);
                sbStack.push(sb);
                multi = 0;
                sb = new StringBuilder();
            } else if (c == ']') {
                StringBuilder tmp = sbStack.pop();
                int count = stack.pop();
                for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
                    tmp.append(sb.toString());
                }
                sb = tmp;
            } else {
                sb.append(c);
            }
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
```

**Complexity**
* Time: O(n)
* Space: O(n)

**Thoughts**
Using two stacks to stimulate the FIFO sequence, one var to record the front element of the queue

**Code**
```java
class MyQueue {
    Stack<Integer> stack1 = new Stack<>();
    Stack<Integer> stack2 = new Stack<>();
    int front;
    public MyQueue() {

    }

    public void push(int x) {
        if (stack1.isEmpty()) {
            front = x;
        }
        while (!stack1.isEmpty()) {
            stack2.push(stack1.pop());
        }
        stack2.push(x);
        while(!stack2.isEmpty()){
            stack1.push(stack2.pop());
        }
    }

    public int pop() {
        int top = stack1.pop();
        if (!stack1.isEmpty()){
            front = stack1.peek();
        }
        return top;
    }

    public int peek() {
        return front;
    }

    public boolean empty() {
        return stack1.isEmpty();
    }
}
```
**Complexity**
* Time: O(1), Push and Pop are constant time
* Space: O(1) no extra space used

